I would have expected [`has`](https://lodash.com/docs#has) to match [`pick`](https://lodash.com/docs#pick) and [`omit`](https://lodash.com/docs#omit)'s signature, whereby extra args beyond the 2nd, or an array as 2nd, get treated as extra properties to check. I think this is the most obvious interpretation of '[support multiple keys](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/issues/750)', since this is assumed wisdom in other object-related methods querying properties. Consider my use case:

``` javascript
// A properly formed 'module' instance has a `controller` and a `view`:
var realModule = {
  controller : function(){},
  view       : function(){}
};

// This one's malformed:
var fakeController = {
    controller : function(){}
};

// ( object, ...string )
var isController = function( x ){
    return _.has( x, 'controller', 'view' );
};

isController( realModule ); // true! :)
isController( fakeModule ); // true! :(

// ( object, string[] )
var isController = function( x ){
    return _.has( x, [ 'controller', 'view' ] );
};

isController( fakeModule ); // false! :)
isController( realModule ); // false! :O
```

